Description

Attack Chain:
Initial Access- Victim phone enters range of rogue tower.
Coercion Phase:
Device forces phone to disconnect from real network.
Phone reconnects to attacker-controlled tower.
Control/Interception:
Attacker now:
Sees device identifiers (IMSI)
Controls messaging channel
Delivery (Smishing):
Sends fake texts:
Banks
Canada Post
Toll services (407 ETR)
Objective:
Credential Theft
Financial Fraud
This bypasses traditional cybersecurity controls entirely. There is no:
Endpoint detection
Antivirus
Email filtering
Network firewall
Because this attack happens at the cellular infrastructure layer.
What breaks normal behavior:
There is a sudden network downgrade from 4G/5G to 2G.
This is often invisible to the user.
There is loss of service:
There is a temporary disconnection.
SMS anomalies:
High-volume messages
Unexpected sender patterns
Urgency + links.
What telemetry exists:
Even though this is RF-layer, there are downstream artifacts:
On the device:
SMS logs
Carrier changes
Signal strength anomalies
On back-end systems:
Fraud detection triggers (bank logins)
Account takeover attempts
On network providers:
Tower handshake anomalies
Rogue base station signatures
